[thinking] **Evaluating Scala testing compatibility**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I need to determine whether I can run Scala tests with different compiler and runtime versions. It seems that I can't have two versions of the scala-library simultaneously. Using a newer compiler might still test against a newer runtime, but I'm not sure if Scala 2.11 will work with JDK 21. An old Scala compiler could be incompatible. If I compile tests with 2.13, the runtime could also require 2.13, making it tricky to test 2.11 directly. I wonder if there’s a way to isolate the classloader to manage versions!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Exploring dynamic class loading**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm considering the dynamic class loading pattern and remembering not to use reflection unless it's within a public API. It seems like Native Image creates challenges since it can't handle open-ended dynamic class loading, making it difficult for tests under Native to run effectively. Perhaps I should think about whether the build can support a separate testImplementation that doesn’t conflict with the scalaClasspath. That might be a way to get around the limitations I’m encountering!
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Evaluating classpath resolution**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m thinking about test runtime classpath resolution and whether it includes both. There’s the question of Gradle's conflict resolution being the highest priority. I could set the resolution strategy to force a specific library version, but that might lead to issues if Scala test code compiled with version 2.13 encounters a NoSuchMethod error with JUnit due to reflection problems. 
[thinking] 
[thinking] Using Scala’s older compiler might keep things simple, but I’m also concerned about compatibility and potential errors if I attempt to run tests in an unsupported environment.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Thinking about compiler usage**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m considering whether I could avoid using the Scala compiler by just placing the .scala test but building with Java. That doesn’t seem right. Maybe I can run my tests with Scala 2.13 if the line bodies are similar. Although, I might get a dynamic access coverage report after running that maps to version 2.13.16, while the user’s active version is 2.11.8. It looks like the build path tested 2.13.16 due to incorrect dependencies, so now I’m wondering where to find the source line in version 2.13.
