o reflection problems. \\n\\nUsing Scala’s older compiler might keep things simple, but I’m also concerned about compatibility and potential errors if I attempt to run tests in an unsupported environment.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Thinking about compiler usage**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I could avoid using the Scala compiler by just placing the .scala test but building with Java. That doesn’t seem right. Maybe I can run my tests with Scala 2.13 if the line bodies are similar. Although, I might get a dynamic access coverage report after running that maps to version 2.13.16, while the user’s active version is 2.11.8. It looks like the build path tested 2.13.16 due to incorrect dependencies, so now I’m wondering where to find the source line in version 2.13.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Mj5oyLnBGsvtY5JQiXSQTGps|fc_0deada2f5b146a450169f8fa51123481959129a42acfe93c8e", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala-library/2.11.8/build/classes/scala/test:$(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.scala-lang/scala-library -path '*2.13.16*/*.jar' | head -1) org_scala_lang.scala_library.Scala_libraryTest 2>/dev/null | head"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 950, "output": 947, "cacheRead": 16896, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 18793, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777924671376, "responseId": "resp_0deada2f5b146a450169f8fa3fde248195bf42917b2f2accb3"}}
