uld keep using the Scala 2.13 compiler but create a tested scala-library jar at runtime through the native/test classpath. Since the bytecode compiled against 2.13 uses certain Scala features, there’s a chance it could be binary incompatible. I want to ensure everything works smoothly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Scala compatibility**\\n\\nI’m thinking about library references and whether Scala code can run properly across different versions, like 2.13 with a 2.11 runtime. Even if they’re binary incompatible, simple code could work, but I should be cautious with library constructs. It seems like running with an older runtime might still be feasible. I'll need to test class bytecode references, and if I'm using JUnit, it's important to consider return types. Lastly, using reflection might be an option if necessary.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating TrieMap compatibility**\\n\\nTo create a TrieMap, I need the class from scala.collection.concurrent, specifically compiled against version 2.13. I’m wondering if it can run with the 2.11 runtime, especially if it has a public no-argument constructor. The methods like put and get may have different signatures, so I should compare them using javap. I also need to consider whether Scala's TrieMap implements Java's ConcurrentMap, which, it seems, it likely does not. I'll check method signatures, especially for update methods. Lastly, configuring the runtime classpath correctly, to prioritize 2.11, seems crucial for proper function.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing runtime configurations**\\n\\nI’m considering how compiler classes require a runtime at times, but for testing, they might not be necessary. It could make sense to configure the test runtime classpath to exclude compiler dependencies and focus on using scala-library version 2.11.8 instead. For a Native Image build, the runtime classpath might include the test runtime classpath, but maintaining the compiler is only crucial for compilation, so I wonder if switching to scalaCompilerPlugins might be the better option for management.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_SVFyCLU3PMzLlIT9Jb8eO7ob|fc_0deada2f5b146a450169f8fb687ec08195b2c9f1e67d33898f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"scalaClasspath|ScalaCompile|zinc\" tests/src build.gradle tck-build-logic -g '*.gradle' -g '*.groovy' | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 660, "output": 1307, "cacheRead": 25600, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 27567, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777924947399, "responseId": "resp_0deada2f5b146a450169f8fb540d1c81959447ddae9ee05d70"}}
