h. Even if conflict resolution selects 2.13, I wonder if I can prepend the specific tested jar file for the runtime or native image classpath. Should I also use TCK (Technology Compatibility Kit)? There's a need to clarify the tasks I need to manage this implementation effectively. It feels essential to be precise in what I’m doing.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Configuring Scala compiler**\\n\\nI need to configure the Scala compiler because I'm having a situation with the `testImplementation`. It seems that `testCompileOnly \\\"org.scala-lang:scala-compiler:2.13.16\\\"` might be enough for ScalaCompile inference but not for runtime. I see that for `testImplementation`, I have 2.11, which creates a compileClasspath conflict favoring 2.13. I confirm that if ScalaCompile infers from compileClasspath, then it can compile fine. It looks like my current build is leading to runtime 2.13, which isn't intended.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting Scala versions**\\n\\nI’m checking how scalac works with different Scala versions at compile time, particularly 2.11 and 2.13. It looks like it creates a scalaClasspath from classpath entries, which seems likely. I need a minimal test source compatible with 2.11, and my current TrieMapTest uses Scala Option which may reference scala.Some$.MODULE$ at runtime for 2.11. However, I’m a bit concerned because the signatures for the TrieMap methods might differ between versions. I'll inspect them using javap for clarity.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_zvw06JZ9AmquVs2C3K5KVlbx|fc_0deada2f5b146a450169f8fb8d2a70819591245cc238a28277", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.scala-lang/scala-library/2.11.8/ddd5a8bced249bedd86fb4578a39b9fb71480573/scala-library-2.11.8.jar 'scala.collection.concurrent.TrieMap' | grep -E 'TrieMap\\(|empty|putIfAbsent|put\\(|get\\(' | head -50"}}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_PrJUHrkpcMuoaXTVbz7dq56K|fc_0deada2